sql:
SELECT CAST(SUM(conference_wins) AS REAL) / SUM(conference_losses) AS conference_win_loss_ratio
FROM conference_records
WHERE season = '2022-2023';

external_knowledge:
- 'ACC' stands for Atlantic Coast Conference, a collegiate athletic conference in the United States;
- 'Top 5' refers to the teams with the highest rankings in terms of overall and conference performance;
- 'Shining both on the national stage and in their conference' metaphorically describes teams that excel in both overall and conference rankings.

- "Top three in their respective conferences" means the teams with the best overall ranks within each conference;
- "2022-2023 season" is the specific season for which the data is being analyzed;
- "Average points scored" is the mean of all points scored by a team in the season.

sql:
SELECT conference_name, founded_year, number_of_teams
FROM conferences
ORDER BY number_of_teams DESC;

external_knowledge:
- The "top 3" refers to the first three positions in the rankings;
- The rankings are specific to the 2022-2023 season;
- The overall rank and conference rank are different metrics used to evaluate team performance.

- "2022-2023 season" refers to the specific sports season being analyzed;
- "scoring prowess" is a metaphorical expression for the average points scored per game;
- "outshines the rest" means having an average points per game greater than 50.

- The "average points scored per game" is calculated by dividing the total points scored in the season by the sum of wins and losses;
- The 2022-2023 season is the latest season for which data is available;
- The threshold of 50 points per game is considered significant in this context.

- "lit up the scoreboard like a fireworks display" refers to teams scoring a high number of points;
- "home arenas" refers to games played at the team's home venue;
- "averaging more than 60 points per game" means the team's average points scored in home games is greater than 60.

- "conference battle scars" refers to the number of wins and losses in conference games;
- "2022-2023 season" is the specific time period for the records being queried;
- "line them up in alphabetical order by their names" means the results are sorted by team name.

- "ancient conferences born before the dawn of the 20th century" refers to conferences founded before the year 1900;
- "grand stadium that can hold more than 10,000 fans" refers to a stadium capacity greater than 10,000;
- "consistently outshone their rivals, winning more games on average than they've lost" refers to the condition where the average number of wins is greater than the average number of losses.

sql:
SELECT SUM(wins) AS total_wins
FROM records
WHERE season = (SELECT MAX(season) FROM records);

external_knowledge:
- "Conference" refers to a group of teams that compete against each other in various sports;
- "Average points" is the sum of points scored by all teams in a conference divided by the number of teams;
- "Top-ranked" means the conference with the highest average points.

- 'founded_year' for conferences and teams refers to the year they were established;
- 'points_for' represents the total points scored by a team in a season;
- The query focuses on conferences and teams established in the 20th century or later.

- "noble teams" refers to the names of the teams;
- "banners of their respective leagues" refers to the names of the conferences;
- "reaped the highest average points" refers to the average points scored by the team across all seasons;
- "guardian of the chronicles" refers to the user who last accessed the records based on the most recent access date.

sql:
SELECT season, conference_wins
FROM conference_records
ORDER BY conference_wins DESC;
